title: Legislative Council Question No. 17 (Written Reply)
question_text: Asked by: Hon Christine LOH Kung-wai Replied by: Secretary for Health and Welfare Question: In relation to the implementation of the Animals (Control of Experiments) Ordinance (Cap. 340) in 1998, will the Administration inform this Council of : (a) the respective numbers of licences granted and renewed under the Ordinance for performing experiments on living vertebrate animals; (b) the number of researchers who were granted more than one licence; (c) the species and the

researchers who were granted more than one licence; (c) the species and the number in each species of animals used in experiments; and (d) the reasons for limiting the purview of the Ordinance only to those experiments performed on animals and calculated to give pain?
reply_text:
Madam President, (a) According to the Animals (Control of Experiments) Ordinance ("the Ordinance"), only persons licensed under section 7 of the Ordinance may perform experiments on living vertebrate animals. In accordance with sections 8, 9 and 10 of the Ordinance, a licensee is required to obtain an additional endorsement or permit from the Department of Health if he/she is to perform experiments :
i) for the purpose of attaining manual skill;
ii) for teaching purpose; or

ii) for teaching purpose; or
iii) without administering any anaesthetics to the animal or without killing the animal before its recovers from the influence of such anaesthetics. In 1998, a total of 583 licences/endorsements/permits were granted by the Department of Health. Among them, 301 were newly granted and 282 were renewals.
